[The level of neurospecific proteins in patients with type 1 diabetes mellitus 
and cognitive disorders].

[Article in Russian]

Novoselova MV, Samoilova IuG, Zhukova NG.

Type I diabetes mellitus (DM1) is a widespread metabolic disease ofsocial 
significance due to early disability in youngpatients and reduced life 
expectancy. One of the DMI complications is CNS lesions resulting in cognitive 
dysfunction mediated through metabolic disorders. This condition can be partly 
or completely reversed if diagnosed and treated'at an early stage. The aim of 
this study was to determine the level ofneurospecific proteins in 58 patients 
aged 16-30years with type I diabetes mellitus and cognitive disorders in 
comparison with 29 healthy controls of simnilar age. All the participants 
underwent neuropsychological testing based on the Montreal scale for rapid 
screening of cognitive disorders (MoCA-test). Protein S100, glial fibrillary 
acidic protein, and myelin basic protein served as early markers of cognitive 
dysfunction. The study revealed an enhanced level of neurospecific proteins that 
correlated with hyperglycemia and cognitive deficit (MoCA score 26).

